</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Interval Estimates</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
</B>
<P>It is good practice to summarise your data by presenting interval estimates for the important parameters (eg <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#109;</FONT>
).   The interval should be accompanied by the probability that the parameter will lie in that interval.</P>

<P>The probability is the <B>level of confidence</B> and the resulting interval is called a <B>confidence interval</B>.</P>

<P>Generally we give a 95% confidence interval but sometimes a 90% or 99% interval is required.</P>

<P>Work through the examples given in your lecture notes pages 5-7.</P>

<P>Try <a href="launch.htm#q0777">q0777</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0778">q0778</a>.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Estimating Sample Size</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
</B>

