<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>The t-distribution</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
</B>
<P>In practice, we rarely know the value of <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#115;</FONT>
.   What we do when <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#115;</FONT>
 is <B>unknown</B> is to estimate it using the sample standard deviation <B>s</B>.</P>

<P>If we use <B>s instead of <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#115;</FONT>
 </B>the z-statistic that we use to calculate confidence intervals becomes a <B>‘t-statistic with n-1 degrees of freedom’</B>.   Often the Greek letter <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#110;</FONT>
 is used to denote degrees of freedom.</P>

<P>The t-distribution is actually a family of distributions since there is a different distribution for each value of <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#110;</FONT>
.  The t-distribution is very similar to the Normal distribution.   As the degrees of freedom (= n-1) increase the percentage points become closer to the equivalent points from the Normal distribution. </P>

<P>Pages 8 and 9 describe the t-distribution.   Work through the example on page 9 then try <a href="launch.htm#q0780">q0780</a>.</P>

